NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) — The chancellor for the board that oversees Tennessee’s technology colleges is recommending that Susanne Cox be appointed as the next president of the College of Applied Technology in Morristown.Chancellor Flora Tydings will recommend Cox to the Board of Regents, which will consider the appointment at its next meeting March 31, the board said Monday.Cox would succeed Jerry Young, who is retiring at the end of April after spending 33 years in the board’s system.Cox has been vice president of TCAT Morristown since 2014. She was one of two finalists selected for the presidency by an 18-member search advisory committee, the board said.The finalists participated in on-campus interviews with the campus community and public on March 14, the board said in a statement.Cox also serves on the board of directors of the Morristown Area Chamber of Commerce.